-- French Stocks Gain for Ninth Day: Alstom, ArcelorMittal, PPR, LVMH Advance
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-21T17:00:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/french-stocks-gain-for-ninth-day-alstom-arcelormittal-ppr-renault-rise.html

          
          
             France’s  CAC 40 Index  climbed 48.94,
or 1.3 percent, to 3,736.15, gaining for a ninth day. That’s the
longest winning streak since July.  The SBF 120 Index  advanced
1.2 percent.  
 Stocks rallied after China signaled it will relax the
yuan’s fixed rate to the dollar. ArcelorMittal, the world’s
biggest steelmaker, jumped 5.7 percent to 26.14 euros. Renault
SA, France’s second-largest carmaker, gained 3.6 percent to
34.06 euros.  
 PPR SA, the owner of Gucci Group, increased 1.1 percent to
107.8 euros. LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA, the world’s
largest maker of luxury goods, jumped 3.4 percent to 96.58
euros.  
 Luxury goods shares rose across Europe.  
 “China is the fastest-growing part of the luxury goods
market,”  Jon Cox , an analyst at Kepler Capital Markets in
Zurich, said by e-mail. “A higher currency boosts sales and
profitability.”  
 The following shares rose or fell in Paris. Stock symbols
are in parentheses.  
 Alstom SA  (ALO FP) advanced 2.3 percent to 41.91 euros,
gaining for a second day. The engineering group signed an
agreement with Russia’s Transmashholding and Kazakh Railways to
create a joint company to produce electric locomotives in
Kazakhstan.  
 Separately, the company said it signed a five-year 107
million-euro ($133 million) maintenance contract with
Stockholmstag.  
 Groupe Eurotunnel SA  (GET FP), operator of the undersea
rail link between England and France, rose 2.6 percent to 6.28
euros, rebounding from three days of losses. The stock entered
the CAC Next 20 Index.  
 GDF Suez SA  (GSZ FP) increased 1.8 percent to 26.3 euros,
erasing the loss of the previous trading session. France’s
largest gas distributor will buy a 9 percent stake in the OAO
Gazprom-led Nord Stream gas pipeline, being built under the
Baltic Sea from Russia to Germany.  
 Ipsen SA  (IPN FP) slipped 2.7 percent to 26.35 euros after
Exane BNP cut its recommendation on the shares to “neutral”
and Portzamparc downgraded the shares to “add.” The stock
plunged 15 percent during the last trading session after Roche
Holding AG delayed development of an experimental diabetes drug
licensed from Ipsen.  
 Stallergenes  (GENP FP) added 1.8 percent to 54.99 euros,
gaining for a second day. Europe’s second-largest maker of
allergy medicines reported positive results in a staloral mites
study in China.  
 Technicolor  (TCH FP) rose 2.1 percent to 54.2 euro cents
after two days of losses. The production and distribution
services company won a 3D World Cup contract with Canal+.  
 Technip SA  (TEC FP), Europe’s second-largest oilfield-
services provider, jumped 5.5 percent to 54.23 euros after crude
rose to the highest in six weeks.  
